    "# Creating Static Maps\n",
    "\n",
    "In this gallery, we will demonstrate the creation of a variety of static maps.\n",
    "Static maps are a good choice for analytical work that will be published in\n",
    "a static document (i.e., on paper, or as a PDF).  In these examples,\n",
    "we will demonstrate creating static maps using [GeoPandas](http://geopandas.org) \n",
    "and [Matplotlib](https://matplotlib.org)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import geopandas as gpd\n",
    "from matplotlib import pyplot as plt"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We'll begin by loading the TAZ and MAZ shapefiles, filtering them to a restricted study area,\n",
    "and defining the center point."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "xmin = 905712\n",
    "ymin = 905343\n",
    "taz = gpd.read_file(tt.data('SERPM8-TAZSHAPE')).cx[xmin:, ymin:]\n",
    "maz = gpd.read_file(tt.data('SERPM8-MAZSHAPE')).cx[xmin:, ymin:]\n",
    "center = (945495, 941036)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Simple Map\n",
    "\n",
    "Simple maps showing the geographic data contained in a GeoDataFrame can be created\n",
    "using the ``plot`` method."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "ax = taz.plot()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The map can be styled to be more legible by passing some styling arguments to the ``plot`` method."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "ax = taz.plot(color='green', linewidth=2, edgecolor='white')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The return value of the ``plot`` method the matplotlib AxesSubplot object\n",
    "on which the map has been drawn.  A new plot is created by default when the\n",
    "``plot`` method is called, but it this can be overridden by passing in to the \n",
    "function an existing AxesSubplot.  This allows drawing multiple different \n",
    "geographic data sets on the same map.  For example, we can draw TAZ's and MAZ's\n",
    "together."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "ax = maz.plot(linewidth=1,  color='green', edgecolor='white')\n",
    "ax = taz.plot(ax=ax, color=(0,0,0,0), linewidth=1, edgecolor='black')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The ability to reuse or modify the AxesSubplot object unlocks all\n",
    "the usual capabilties of the matplotlib package.  We can use the typical \n",
    "matplotlib tools for figure creation and manipulation to customize the \n",
    "map as desired, including changing labels, borders, fonts, etc.\n",
    "For example:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 864x648 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12,9))\n",
    "ax.axis('on')      # do show axis as a frame\n",
    "ax.set_xticks([])  # but no tick marks\n",
    "ax.set_yticks([])  # one either axis\n",
    "ax.set_title(\"SERPM 8 Zones\", fontweight='bold', fontsize=16, pad=20)\n",
    "ax.annotate('in the viscinity of Jupiter, FL', \n",
    "            xy=(0.5, 1.0), xycoords='axes fraction', \n",
    "            xytext=(0, 5), textcoords='offset points',\n",
    "            horizontalalignment='center',\n",
    "            fontstyle='italic')\n",
    "from matplotlib.lines import Line2D\n",
    "legend_elements = [\n",
    "    Line2D([0], [0], color='black', linewidth=1, label='TAZ'),\n",
    "    Line2D([0], [0], color='red', linewidth=0.5, label='MAZ'),\n",
    "]\n",
    "ax.legend(handles=legend_elements, title='Legend')\n",
    "ax = maz.plot(ax=ax, linewidth=0.5,  color='white', edgecolor='red', label='MAZ')\n",
    "ax = taz.plot(ax=ax, color=(0,0,0,0), linewidth=1, edgecolor='black')"
   ]
  },

    "We can join the demographics table to the shape file we loaded previously,\n",
    "to enable some visualizations on this data.  This can be done with the\n",

   ]

  {

    "maz1 = maz.merge(mazd, how='left', left_on='MAZ', right_on='mgra')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Choropleth Maps\n",
    "\n",
    "A [choropleth map](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Choropleth_map) is a map with areas colored, \n",
    "shaded, or patterned in proportion to some measured value for the region displayed. This kind of\n",
    "map is commonly used to display things like population density.\n",
    "\n",
    "A GeoDataFrame can be used to create a choropleth map simply by passing a column name to\n",
    "the ``plot`` method, where the named column contains the data to be displayed."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 864x648 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12,9))\n",
    "ax.axis('off') # don't show axis\n",
    "ax.set_title(\"Population Density\", fontweight='bold', fontsize=16)\n",
    "ax = maz1.plot(ax=ax, column='PopDen')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "You can also add a legend easily."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 864x648 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12,9))\n",
    "ax.axis('off') # don't show axis\n",
    "ax.set_title(\"Population Density\", fontweight='bold', fontsize=16)\n",
    "ax = maz1.plot(ax=ax, column='PopDen', legend=True)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Or change the colors, by giving a ``cmap`` argument.  Any \n",
    "[named colormap](https://matplotlib.org/tutorials/colors/colormaps.html)\n",
    "from matplotlib can be used."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {
    "scrolled": false
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 864x648 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12,9))\n",
    "ax.axis('off') # don't show axis\n",
    "ax.set_title(\"Population Density\", fontweight='bold', fontsize=16)\n",
    "ax = maz1.plot(ax=ax, column='PopDen', legend=True, cmap='OrRd')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can also apply various other commands from matplotlib.  For example, we\n",
    "can use `annotate` to write the MAZ id's onto the map.  We'll only write them\n",
    "on MAZ's that are sufficiently large areas that the map won't appear as a \n",
    "jumble of labels."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 864x648 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "def annotate_map(ax, gdf, annot, row_slice=slice(None), **kwargs):\n",
    "    gdf.loc[row_slice].apply(\n",
    "        lambda x: ax.annotate(\n",
    "            s=annot.format(**x), \n",
    "            xy=x.geometry.centroid.coords[0], \n",
    "            horizontalalignment='center',\n",
    "            **kwargs,\n",
    "        ),\n",
    "        axis=1,\n",
    "    )\n",
    "    \n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12,9))\n",
    "ax.axis('off') # don't show axis\n",
    "ax.set_title(\"Population Density\", fontweight='bold', fontsize=16)\n",
    "ax = maz1.plot(ax=ax, column='PopDen', legend=True)\n",
    "annotate_map(ax, maz1, '{MAZ}', maz1.apply(lambda x: x.geometry.area > 1e7, axis=1), color='w')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "pycharm": {
     "name": "#%% md\n"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "### Adding a Background"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "source": [
    "If we would like some additional context for the map, we can add a background layer with some\n",
    "familiar map content.  To do so, we will need to get some map tiles (rendered map pieces), and we can use\n",
    "[contextily](https://github.com/darribas/contextily) to help automate this."
   ],
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   }
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import contextily as ctx\n",
    "\n",
    "def add_basemap(ax, zoom, url='http://tile.stamen.com/terrain/tileZ/tileX/tileY.png'):\n",
    "    xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax = ax.axis()\n",
    "    basemap, extent = ctx.bounds2img(xmin, ymin, xmax, ymax, zoom=zoom, url=url)\n",
    "    ax.imshow(basemap, extent=extent, interpolation='bilinear')\n",
    "    # restore original x/y limits\n",
    "    ax.axis((xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    attribution_txt = \"Map tiles by Stamen Design, under CC BY 3.0. Data by OpenStreetMap, under ODbL.\"\n",
    "    ax.annotate(\n",
    "        attribution_txt,\n",
    "        xy=(1.0, 0.0), xycoords='axes fraction',\n",
    "        xytext=(0, -10), textcoords='offset points',\n",
    "        horizontalalignment='right',\n",
    "        fontstyle='italic',\n",
    "        fontsize=8,\n",
    "    )\n",
    "\n",
    "    return ax"
   ],
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false,
    "pycharm": {
     "name": "#%%\n"
    }
   }
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Web map tiles are typically provided in\n",
    "[Web Mercator](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_Mercator)\n",
    "[EPSG 3857](https://epsg.io/3857), so we need to make sure to convert\n",
    "our data first to the same CRS to combine our polygons and background tiles\n",
    "in the same map."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import contextily as ctx\n",
    "\n",
    "def add_basemap(ax, zoom, url='http://tile.stamen.com/terrain/tileZ/tileX/tileY.png'):\n",
    "    xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax = ax.axis()\n",
    "    basemap, extent = ctx.bounds2img(xmin, ymin, xmax, ymax, zoom=zoom, url=url)\n",
    "    ax.imshow(basemap, extent=extent, interpolation='bilinear')\n",
    "    # restore original x/y limits\n",
    "    ax.axis((xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    attribution_txt = \"Map tiles by Stamen Design, under CC BY 3.0. Data by OpenStreetMap, under ODbL.\"\n",
    "    ax.annotate(\n",
    "        attribution_txt,\n",
    "        xy=(1.0, 0.0), xycoords='axes fraction',\n",
    "        xytext=(0, -10), textcoords='offset points',\n",
    "        horizontalalignment='right',\n",
    "        fontstyle='italic',\n",
    "        fontsize=8,\n",
    "    )\n",
    "\n",
    "    return ax"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Web map tiles are typically provided in\n",
    "[Web Mercator](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_Mercator)\n",
    "[EPSG 3857](https://epsg.io/3857), so we need to make sure to convert\n",
    "our data first to the same CRS to combine our polygons and background tiles\n",
    "in the same map."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "maz2 = maz1.to_crs(epsg=3857)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Then we can create the map.  We set the ``alpha`` (opacity) of the choropleth\n",
    "plot itself to be only 0.6, so we can see the map tile detail underneath the \n",
    "colors."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 864x648 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12,9))\n",
    "ax.axis('off') # don't show axis\n",
    "ax.set_title(\"Population Density\", fontweight='bold', fontsize=16)\n",
    "ax = maz2.plot(ax=ax, alpha=0.6, linewidth=0, cmap='viridis', column='PopDen', legend=True)\n",
    "ax = add_basemap(ax, zoom=12, url=ctx.sources.ST_TONER_LITE)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",

   "source": [
    "## Dot Density Map"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "For certain kinds of data, it might make sense to plot a dot density map instead \n",
    "of a choropleth.\n",
    "\n",
    "We'll use some code from the tutorials package to generate a dot density map\n",
    "the shows population density in each MAZ."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,

       "</style>\n",
       "<div class=\"pygments\"><pre><span></span><span class=\"c1\"># Code based on an original given in</span>\n",
       "<span class=\"c1\"># https://github.com/agaidus/census_data_extraction/blob/master/census_mapper.py</span>\n",
       "\n",
       "<span class=\"kn\">import</span> <span class=\"nn\">geopandas</span> <span class=\"k\">as</span> <span class=\"nn\">gpd</span>\n",
       "<span class=\"kn\">import</span> <span class=\"nn\">pandas</span> <span class=\"k\">as</span> <span class=\"nn\">pd</span>\n",
       "<span class=\"kn\">from</span> <span class=\"nn\">shapely.geometry</span> <span class=\"kn\">import</span> <span class=\"n\">Point</span>\n",
       "<span class=\"kn\">from</span> <span class=\"nn\">numpy.random</span> <span class=\"kn\">import</span> <span class=\"n\">RandomState</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">uniform</span>\n",
       "\n",
       "\n",
       "<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"nf\">generate_random_points_in_polygon</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">poly</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">num_points</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">seed</span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"kc\">None</span><span class=\"p\">):</span>\n",
       "\t<span class=\"sd\">&quot;&quot;&quot;</span>\n",
       "<span class=\"sd\">\tCreate a list of randomly generated points within a polygon.</span>\n",
       "\n",
       "<span class=\"sd\">\tParameters</span>\n",
       "<span class=\"sd\">\t----------</span>\n",
       "<span class=\"sd\">\tpoly : Polygon</span>\n",
       "<span class=\"sd\">\tnum_points : int</span>\n",
       "<span class=\"sd\">\t\tThe number of random points to create within the polygon</span>\n",
       "<span class=\"sd\">\tseed : int, optional</span>\n",
       "<span class=\"sd\">\t\tA random seed</span>\n",
       "\n",
       "<span class=\"sd\">\tReturns</span>\n",
       "<span class=\"sd\">\t-------</span>\n",
       "<span class=\"sd\">\tList</span>\n",
       "<span class=\"sd\">\t&quot;&quot;&quot;</span>\n",
       "\t<span class=\"n\">min_x</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">min_y</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">max_x</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">max_y</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"n\">poly</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">bounds</span>\n",
       "\t<span class=\"n\">points</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"p\">[]</span>\n",
       "\t<span class=\"n\">i</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"mi\">0</span>\n",
       "\t<span class=\"k\">while</span> <span class=\"nb\">len</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">points</span><span class=\"p\">)</span> <span class=\"o\">&lt;</span> <span class=\"n\">num_points</span><span class=\"p\">:</span>\n",
       "\t\t<span class=\"n\">s</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"n\">RandomState</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">seed</span> <span class=\"o\">+</span> <span class=\"n\">i</span><span class=\"p\">)</span> <span class=\"k\">if</span> <span class=\"n\">seed</span> <span class=\"k\">else</span> <span class=\"n\">RandomState</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">seed</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n",
       "\t\t<span class=\"n\">random_point</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"n\">Point</span><span class=\"p\">([</span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">uniform</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">min_x</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">max_x</span><span class=\"p\">),</span> <span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">uniform</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">min_y</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">max_y</span><span class=\"p\">)])</span>\n",
       "\t\t<span class=\"k\">if</span> <span class=\"n\">random_point</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">within</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">poly</span><span class=\"p\">):</span>\n",
       "\t\t\t<span class=\"n\">points</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">append</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">random_point</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n",
       "\t\t<span class=\"n\">i</span> <span class=\"o\">+=</span> <span class=\"mi\">1</span>\n",
       "\t<span class=\"k\">return</span> <span class=\"n\">points</span>\n",
       "\n",
       "\n",
       "<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"nf\">generate_points_in_areas</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">gdf</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">values</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">points_per_unit</span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">seed</span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"kc\">None</span><span class=\"p\">):</span>\n",
       "\t<span class=\"sd\">&quot;&quot;&quot;</span>\n",
       "<span class=\"sd\">\tCreate a GeoSeries of random points in polygons.</span>\n",
       "\n",
       "<span class=\"sd\">\tParameters</span>\n",
       "<span class=\"sd\">\t----------</span>\n",
       "<span class=\"sd\">\tgdf : GeoDataFrame</span>\n",
       "<span class=\"sd\">\t\tThe areas in which to create points</span>\n",
       "<span class=\"sd\">\tvalues : str or Series</span>\n",
       "<span class=\"sd\">\t\tThe [possibly scaled] number of points to create in each area</span>\n",
       "<span class=\"sd\">\tpoints_per_unit : numeric, optional</span>\n",
       "<span class=\"sd\">\t\tThe rate to scale the values in point generation.</span>\n",
       "<span class=\"sd\">\tseed : int, optional</span>\n",
       "<span class=\"sd\">\t\tA random seed</span>\n",
       "\n",
       "<span class=\"sd\">\tReturns</span>\n",
       "<span class=\"sd\">\t-------</span>\n",
       "<span class=\"sd\">\tGeoSeries</span>\n",
       "<span class=\"sd\">\t&quot;&quot;&quot;</span>\n",
       "\t<span class=\"n\">geometry</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"n\">gdf</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">geometry</span>\n",
       "\t<span class=\"k\">if</span> <span class=\"nb\">isinstance</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">values</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"nb\">str</span><span class=\"p\">)</span> <span class=\"ow\">and</span> <span class=\"n\">values</span> <span class=\"ow\">in</span> <span class=\"n\">gdf</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">columns</span><span class=\"p\">:</span>\n",
       "\t\t<span class=\"n\">values</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"n\">gdf</span><span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"n\">values</span><span class=\"p\">]</span>\n",
       "\t<span class=\"n\">new_values</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">values</span> <span class=\"o\">/</span> <span class=\"n\">points_per_unit</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">astype</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nb\">int</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n",
       "\t<span class=\"n\">g</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"n\">gpd</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">GeoDataFrame</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">data</span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"p\">{</span><span class=\"s1\">&#39;vals&#39;</span><span class=\"p\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">new_values</span><span class=\"p\">},</span> <span class=\"n\">geometry</span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"n\">geometry</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n",
       "\t<span class=\"n\">a</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"n\">g</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">apply</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"k\">lambda</span> <span class=\"n\">row</span><span class=\"p\">:</span> <span class=\"nb\">tuple</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">generate_random_points_in_polygon</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">row</span><span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"s1\">&#39;geometry&#39;</span><span class=\"p\">],</span> <span class=\"n\">row</span><span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"s1\">&#39;vals&#39;</span><span class=\"p\">],</span> <span class=\"n\">seed</span><span class=\"p\">)),</span> <span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n",
       "\t<span class=\"n\">b</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"n\">gpd</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">GeoSeries</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">apply</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">pd</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Series</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">stack</span><span class=\"p\">(),</span> <span class=\"n\">crs</span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"n\">geometry</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">crs</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n",
       "\t<span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">name</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"s1\">&#39;geometry&#39;</span>\n",
       "\t<span class=\"k\">return</span> <span class=\"n\">b</span>\n",
       "</pre></div>\n",
       "\n"
      ],
      "text/plain": [

   ]

    "emp_points = tt.tools.point_map.generate_points_in_areas(maz2, values='emp_total', points_per_unit=25)"
   ]

    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12,9))\n",
    "ax.axis('on')      # do show axis as a frame\n",
    "ax.set_xticks([])  # but no tick marks\n",
    "ax.set_yticks([])  # one either axis\n",
    "ax.set_title(\"Employment, All Categories\", fontweight='bold', fontsize=16, pad=20)\n",
    "ax = emp_points.plot(ax=ax, markersize=1, alpha=0.33)\n",
    "ax.annotate('Each point represents 25 jobs', \n",
    "            xy=(0.5, 1.0), xycoords='axes fraction', \n",
    "            xytext=(0, 5), textcoords='offset points',\n",
    "           horizontalalignment='center',\n",
    "           fontstyle='italic')\n",
    "ax = add_basemap(ax, zoom=12, url=ctx.sources.ST_TONER_LITE)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "It is also possible to plot multiple different sets of dot density data\n",
    "on the same map.  In the following example, we pull out retail and healthcare\n",
    "employment, and plot those in different colors."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 23,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "i = 'retail'\n",
    "j = 'health'\n",
    "i_points = tt.tools.point_map.generate_points_in_areas(maz2, values=f'emp_{i}', points_per_unit=25)\n",
    "j_points = tt.tools.point_map.generate_points_in_areas(maz2, values=f'emp_{j}', points_per_unit=25)\n",
    "maz2[f'emp_allother'] = maz2.emp_total - maz2[f'emp_{i}'] - maz2[f'emp_{j}']\n",
    "o_points = tt.tools.point_map.generate_points_in_areas(maz2, values=f'emp_allother', points_per_unit=25)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 24,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 864x648 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12,9))\n",
    "ax.axis('on')      # do show axis as a frame\n",
    "ax.set_xticks([])  # but no tick marks\n",
    "ax.set_yticks([])  # one either axis\n",
    "ax.set_title(\"Employment, Various Categories\", fontweight='bold', fontsize=16, pad=20)\n",
    "ax = i_points.plot(ax=ax, markersize=1, alpha=0.33, color='red')\n",
    "ax = j_points.plot(ax=ax, markersize=1, alpha=0.33, color='green')\n",
    "ax = o_points.plot(ax=ax, markersize=1, alpha=0.33)\n",
    "legend_elements = [\n",
    "    Line2D([0], [0], marker='o', lw=0, color='red', label='Retail'),\n",
    "    Line2D([0], [0], marker='o', lw=0, color='green', label='Healthcare'),\n",
    "    Line2D([0], [0], marker='o', lw=0, color='blue', label='Other'),\n",
    "]\n",
    "ax.legend(handles=legend_elements, title='Legend')\n",
    "ax.annotate('Each point represents 25 jobs', \n",
    "            xy=(0.5, 1.0), xycoords='axes fraction', \n",
    "            xytext=(0, 5), textcoords='offset points',\n",
    "           horizontalalignment='center',\n",
    "           fontstyle='italic')\n",
    "ax = add_basemap(ax, zoom=12, url=ctx.sources.ST_TONER_LITE)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Using different colored points helps to highlight important traffic generators, including the \n",
    "Scripps Research Institute (green, on Donald Ross Road) and the Gardens Mall (red)."
   ]
  }
